I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation able to create connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We came of age during a media golden age, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations of our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are all available at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified closed spaces.
consciously we are dying to connect to the universal community surrounding all of this
that's why so many of us are obsessed with watching series like The Office or movies like The Late Show, full of short references, like memes.
we would repeat these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we cannot know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize everything... will we escape hyper-saturation?
we are caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter parasocial relationships with more attention.
we understand that it is hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
due to a lack of collective consciousness in the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
some of us continue to place people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall from it.
we are in a turbulent period and I am eager to know where it will take us.
